            <section class="page" id="page-2.1">
                <div class="content-card">
                    <button class="listen-btn" onclick="speakPage('page-2.1')">🔊 Listen to Page</button>
                    <h2>2.1 What are Living Organisms Made of?</h2>
                    <p>All living things are made of <strong>cells</strong>. A cell is the smallest unit of life that can carry out all basic activities — eating, breathing, growing, and reproducing — on its own.</p>
                    <div class="analogy-box">
                        <strong>🧱 Brick-and-Wall Analogy</strong>
                        <p>Just as a wall is built from bricks, your body is built from cells. Each cell is small and simple, but together they form a complex living being.</p>
                    </div>
                    <h3>🔬 The Onion Peel Mount Experiment</h3>
                    <p>Take a thin layer of onion peel, place it on a glass slide, add a drop of water and a stain (like iodine), and cover with a cover slip. Look under a microscope — you'll see tiny <strong>box-like structures</strong> arranged like a honeycomb. Those are <strong>plant cells</strong> with visible cell walls and nuclei.</p>

                    <h3>📜 Historical Discovery Table</h3>
                    <div class="table-wrap">
                        <table>
                            <thead><tr><th>Scientist</th><th>Year</th><th>Discovery</th></tr></thead>
                            <tbody>
                                <tr><td>Robert Hooke</td><td>1665</td><td>Observed cork cells under a microscope; named them "cells" (small rooms).</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>Anton van Leeuwenhoek</td><td>1674</td><td>First to see <strong>living</strong> cells — tiny organisms in pond water.</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>Robert Brown</td><td>1831</td><td>Discovered the <strong>nucleus</strong> inside plant cells.</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>Purkinje</td><td>1839</td><td>Coined the term <strong>"protoplasm"</strong> for the living fluid inside cells.</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>Schleiden &amp; Schwann</td><td>1838–39</td><td>Proposed the <strong>Cell Theory</strong> (plants &amp; animals are made of cells).</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>Rudolf Virchow</td><td>1855</td><td>Stated that all cells arise from <strong>pre-existing cells</strong>.</td></tr>
                            </tbody>
                        </table>
                    </div>

                    <h3>📌 The Three Core Rules of Cell Theory</h3>
                    <ol>
                        <li><strong>All living organisms</strong> are made of one or more cells.</li>
                        <li>The <strong>cell</strong> is the basic unit of structure and function in living things.</li>
                        <li>All new cells come from <strong>already existing cells</strong> (by division).</li>
                    </ol>
                    <div class="analogy-box">
                        <strong>🧱 Easy Example</strong>
                        <p>Cell Theory is like saying: "Every house is made of bricks, and every new brick comes from a brick factory." Every living thing is made of cells, and every new cell comes from an old cell splitting.</p>
                    </div>

