                    <h2>2.2 What is the Structural Organisation of a Cell?</h2>
                    <p>Inside a cell, different parts do different jobs — this is called <strong>division of labour</strong>. Just like a factory has separate departments, a cell has specialized structures called <strong>organelles</strong>.</p>
                    <p>Almost every cell has three basic features:</p>
                    <ol>
                        <li><strong>Plasma Membrane</strong> — the outer boundary.</li>
                        <li><strong>Nucleus</strong> — the control centre.</li>
                        <li><strong>Cytoplasm</strong> — the jelly-like filling.</li>
                    </ol>
                    <div class="analogy-box">
                        <strong>🏭 Easy Example</strong>
                        <p>A cell is like a factory: the nucleus is the manager's office, the cytoplasm is the workshop floor, and the membrane is the factory wall with gates.</p>
