                    <button class="listen-btn" onclick="speakPage('page-2.2.1')">🔊 Listen to Page</button>
                    <h2>2.2.1 Plasma Membrane (Cell Membrane)</h2>
                    <p>The <strong>plasma membrane</strong> is the thin, flexible outer covering of every cell. It is made mainly of <strong>lipids</strong> (fats) and <strong>proteins</strong>. It is <strong>selectively permeable</strong> — it allows some substances to pass through but blocks others.</p>
                    <div class="analogy-box">
                        <strong>🚪 Security Guard Analogy</strong>
                        <p>The membrane is like a security guard at a gate: it lets in useful substances (food, oxygen) and keeps out harmful ones, while allowing waste to leave.</p>
                    </div>

                    <h3>🔁 Diffusion</h3>
                    <p><strong>Diffusion</strong> is the movement of particles (gases, liquids) from a region of <strong>high concentration</strong> to <strong>low concentration</strong> until evenly spread. Example: CO₂ and O₂ move in and out of cells this way.</p>
