            <section class="page" id="page-2.2.2">
                <div class="content-card">
                    <button class="listen-btn" onclick="speakPage('page-2.2.2')">🔊 Listen to Page</button>
                    <h2>2.2.2 Cell Wall</h2>
                    <p>The <strong>cell wall</strong> is a tough, rigid, non-living outer layer found in <strong>plants, fungi, and bacteria</strong> (but <em>not</em> in animal cells). In plants, it's made of <strong>cellulose</strong>.</p>
                    <p><strong>Functions:</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Provides extra strength and support.</li>
                        <li>Gives the cell a <strong>fixed box-like shape</strong>.</li>
                        <li>Prevents the cell from bursting when water enters by osmosis — it exerts <strong>counter-pressure</strong>.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <div class="analogy-box">
                        <strong>📦 Balloon-in-a-Box Analogy</strong>
                        <p>The cell membrane is like a thin balloon, and the cell wall is like a <strong>cardboard box</strong> around it. The box keeps the balloon from expanding too much and gives it a rigid shape. Animal cells have no box — they stay rounded and flexible.</p>
                    </div>
