                    <h2>2.2.3 Nucleus — The Control Centre</h2>
                    <p>The <strong>nucleus</strong> is the round, dense structure that controls all cell activities. It is covered by a <strong>double-layered nuclear membrane</strong> with tiny <strong>nuclear pores</strong> that let materials move in and out. Inside is the dense <strong>nucleolus</strong>, which makes ribosomes.</p>
                    <p><strong>Genetic Blueprint:</strong> The nucleus contains <strong>DNA</strong> (the hereditary material). In resting cells, DNA is in the form of tangled <strong>chromatin</strong>. During cell division, it condenses into rod-shaped <strong>chromosomes</strong>. <strong>Genes</strong> are units of heredity on the DNA.</p>

