                    <h2>2.3.1 Endoplasmic Reticulum (ER)</h2>
                    <p>The <strong>ER</strong> is a vast continuous network of tubes and sheets spreading through the cytoplasm. It is connected to the nuclear membrane.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Rough ER (RER)</strong> — has <strong>ribosomes</strong> on its surface (looks "rough"). It synthesizes and folds <strong>proteins</strong>.</li>
                        <li><strong>Smooth ER (SER)</strong> — no ribosomes. It manufactures <strong>lipids</strong> (fats) and <strong>hormones</strong>, and detoxifies poisons.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p><strong>Membrane Biogenesis:</strong> The cell uses its own made proteins and lipids to build and repair cell membranes.</p>
                    <div class="analogy-box">
                        <strong>🚚 Transport Highway</strong>
                        <p>The ER is like the <strong>corridors and conveyor belts</strong> of a factory — moving materials from one department to another.</p>
