                    <h2>⚠️ Unregulated Division — Cancer</h2>
                    <p>Normal cells follow a rule called <strong>contact inhibition</strong> — they stop dividing when they touch neighbouring cells. This prevents overcrowding.</p>
                    <p>In <strong>cancer</strong>, cells lose this rule and divide out of control, forming a lump called a <strong>tumour</strong>. These cells ignore the "stop dividing" signal and keep multiplying.</p>
                    <p>In plants, similar uncontrolled growth can cause <strong>crown gall disease</strong> (tumour-like growths).</p>
                    <div class="analogy-box">
                        <strong>🚇 Lift Analogy</strong>
                        <p>Imagine people in a lift — once it's full, people stop entering (contact inhibition). In cancer, this rule is broken, and cells keep forcing their way in even when there's no space, causing chaos (a tumour).</p>
